priceless <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  . <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub14.ezboard.com/ushikariiapoccalypse.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Shikarii Apoccalypse</A> at: 9/3/02 10:44:36 am<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub14.ezboard.com/uketherami.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Kether Am I</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>knows that Warriors are superior</span><br>  Posts: 11<br> <font color=#FF0000>(9/3/02 12:06:26 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub14.ezboard.com/fthesteelwarriorthetavern.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1184.topic&index=20>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Direction of Warriors</span><hr size=1> Honestly, those who focus on 'pal/sk are almost as good as warriors and they get SPELLS' are really missing the current glaring problems in EQ.  VI (in order to make encounters 'challenging') have once again exacerbated vast differences between optimized and representative raid forces through ignorant itemization.  Furthermore XP settings have to continually push the 'tanking envelope'.<br>
<br>
Right now there is a 'plate' problem.  It isn't warrior specific although warriors are the most disadvanated atm.<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
1. Raids<br>
<br>
<br>
The 'useful' spells a paladin has on a raid are:<br>
<br>
Brells<br>
Healing Wave of Prexus<br>
Stuns (for positioning mobs and locking up adds)<br>
Superior Heal (cast time/hp healed on it make it from marginal to somewhat useful depending on target)<br>
<br>
There is a 52 point (~150 atk) difference between war and knights.  That coupled with warriors possessing triple attack, flurry, and ambi probably account for a 80/100 dps ratio between them.  (I am not counting SU3.  If I raid 30 mobs in a week and 2 are undead I am lucky.  If you want to average it in then say 81/100, but to use SU3 dps as representative is misleading.  I could put in 32k mob, who I fight more than I do undead ones, dps where warrior with their discipline do too much damage relative to paladins.)                      <br>
<br>
An FD monk with rez stick is much more useful than a paladin rez in most raid settings.  HP are lower, d/p/r are lower.  No damage reduction discipline.  But they do present huge taunt potential.                     <br>
<br>
In a raid setting I think the pal/war are actually fairly well balanced.  On non ae mobs warriors (via higher dps when non defensive and the ability to go aggressive) are better iteratively.  On 'reasonable' AE mobs paladins via their group heal and 80% ish damage are better iteratively.<br>
<br>
More than *anything else* dps need to be brought back to the roughly 0.8/1.0/1.2/1.4 numbers.<br>
<br>
Secondly, give a final damage reduction factor.  This reduces the minimum as well as avg or max hit.  Make it 0% for silk/leather, make it 5% for chain, make it 10% for bards, clerics, make it 20% for knights, and 30% for warriors.<br>
<br>
Leave defensive in.  Will that 'trivialize' things that are hard now?  Sure.  But if you take it out you then have to jack up the warrior reduction factor even higher to balance them against other classes.<br>
<br>
Thats what happens over time in EQ.  Everything becomes easier.  It leave you a choice, do you:<br>
<br>
a. Let a defensive warrior tank (with transistions).<br>
b. Let a sole warrior tank from beginning to end.<br>
c. Let a knight tank.<br>
d. Let others tank (should not be more than a very short speed bump, and never desirable).<br>
<br>
The reason why I would modify it as above is that each a-c has its advantages.  A is the least mana intensive (by *far*) but may result in a longer fight from reduced force DPS.  C is the most mana intensive of the three, but with the most room for sloppy aggro.  B is a solid middle choice between A and C.<br>
<br>
Warriors (and ONLY warriors) should have a gauranteed minimum hate added from use of taunt skill.  Maybe 5 points per mob level.  Play with the numbers.  That would be 350 points per press of taunt.  If successful the taunt places them +350 points hate or on top of list (whichever is greater).  If it doesn't succeed it places them 350 points higher than before.  This helps to moderate the taunting edge that knights currently have.  Knights will still be able to outaggro and frankly with weaker defensive abilities that is the only thing that even makes them viable.  Run the numbers, maybe that is too much presenting no aggro control problems at all, maybe its too little.  Put in some numbers, run tests, find a nice point where a force with a defensive warrior can manage aggro if they work together.<br>
<br>
Oh, given the above changes outright remove any and ALL direct hate modifying procs.  For example, take EB off BoCs and put on a 150pt no resist dd proc on them instead.<br>
<br>
<br>
2.  XP<br>
<br>
The damage reduction factor and taunt improvements will help while XPing too.  With increased XP for higher level mobs this will help warriors get more 'good xp'.  An additional 2-3 CT like zones will help as well.  If done right no one would want to 'solo' for XP.  With this the case it must not be overdone as sk only other role for group (pulling) is much better done by monks in most cases and paladins have no real group role outside of tank in places like CT.  In that setting the higher dps of a warrior, better mitigation, better avoidance, and ability to go defensive would very favorably match up with the better aggro and utility of the knight classes.<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
Kether<br>
Crusader - E'ci<br>
